# Self-Maintenance and Drift Control

Prevent drift across engine implementation, runtime contracts, docs, rules, agents, and skills.

Post-migration policy: treat active runtime contracts and quality gates as steady-state architecture, not temporary migration scaffolding.
End-state hygiene: remove stale migration-era names/labels/docs from canonical surfaces once migration is complete.

## 1) No-Drift Requirement

When behavior, contracts, APIs, naming, or architecture changes:

- Update canonical docs first (`llms.txt`, `docs/**`, `design/**`, canonical rules).
- Update engine/runtime code paths that implement the changed contract in the same session (`src/**`, `wasm/**` as applicable).
- Update affected `.cursor/rules/**`, `.cursor/agents/**`, and `.cursor/skills/**` in the same session.
- Remove stale instructions instead of keeping old and new guidance in parallel.

## 2) Drift Audit Triggers

Run a focused drift audit whenever changes touch:

- `src/core/PluginRegistry.ts` or plugin interface/hook contracts
- runtime/save-load/event contracts in `src/**` and related runtime paths (`wasm/**` when in scope)
- plugin lifecycle, prewarm, terrain-dispatch, autosave-intent, or HMR worker lifecycle policies
- interaction-hitch methodology, diagnostics preset workflow, or first-look performance guidance
- non-obvious targeted fixes or local guardrails whose rationale must stay visible at the exact code site
- palette/tooling architecture (`PaletteRegistry`, `ToolPalette`, placement workflows)
- component registration patterns or save/load contract schemas
- canonical plugin/event documentation sections in `llms.txt`

## 3) Freshness Metadata

- Any updated rule/agent/skill must refresh frontmatter `lastReviewed` (`YYYY-MM-DD`).
- New rule/agent/skill files must include `lastReviewed` at creation.

## 4) Agent Routing for Maintenance

- Use `migration-and-terminology` for field/type/API/terminology replacements.
- Use `architecture-and-docs` after behavior/contract changes to verify canonical sync.
- Use `verifier` for non-trivial maintenance passes before handoff when scope is broad.

## 5) Done Criteria

- No stale implementation paths remain in touched engine/runtime areas (`src/**`, `wasm/**`).
- If behavior changed, implementation and docs are both updated in the same session (code + canonical docs + derived guidance).
- Non-obvious targeted fixes keep a local rationale comment near the code that enforces them, so future readers know what bug/regression the guard is preventing.
- No contradictory guidance remains across:
  - `src/**` (behavior/contracts)
  - `wasm/**` (when in scope)
  - `.cursor/rules/**`
  - `.cursor/agents/**`
  - `.cursor/skills/**`
  - `llms.txt`
  - `docs/**`
  - `design/**`
- Hitch/performance postmortem lessons that change first-look guidance are reflected in canonical docs and debugging guidance, not left only in ad hoc chat history.
- Touched governance files include updated `lastReviewed`.
